    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "2. We use the following scheme to solve the PDE $u _ { t } + u _ { x } = 0$ : ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            630,
            734,
            646
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\nu _ {j} ^ {n + 1} = a u _ {j - 2} ^ {n} + b u _ {j - 1} ^ {n} + c u _ {j} ^ {n}\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            376,
            651,
            618,
            671
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "where ∆x $\\frac { \\Delta t } { \\Delta x }$ . Here $a$ , $b$ $x _ { j } = j \\Delta x$ , $c$ are constants which may depend on the CFL number , $t ^ { n } = n \\Delta t$ and $u _ { j } ^ { n }$ is the numerical approximation $\\lambda =$ to the exact solution $u ( x _ { j } , t ^ { n } )$ , with periodic boundary conditions. ",
        "bbox": [
            193,
            675,
            801,
            725
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "list",
        "sub_type": "text",
        "list_items": [
            "(i) Find $a$ , $b$ , $c$ so that the scheme is second order accurate. ",
            "(ii) Verify that the scheme you derived in Part (i) is exact (i.e. $u _ { j } ^ { n } =$ $u ( x _ { j } , t ^ { n } ) )$ if $\\lambda = 1$ or $\\lambda = 2$ . Does this imply that the scheme is stable for $\\lambda \\leq 2 ^ { \\cdot }$ ? If not, find $\\lambda _ { 0 }$ such that the scheme is stable for $\\lambda \\le \\lambda _ { 0 }$ . Recall that a scheme is stable if there exist constants $M$ and $C$ , which are independent of the mesh sizes $\\Delta x$ and $\\Delta t$ , such that "
        ],
        "bbox": [
            191,
            726,
            801,
            825
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "text": "$$\n\\| u ^ {n} \\| \\leq M e ^ {C T} \\| u ^ {0} \\|\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            416,
            829,
            581,
            848
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "for all $\\Delta x$ , $\\Delta t$ and $n$ such that $t ^ { n } \\leq T$ . You can use either the $L ^ { \\infty }$ norm or the $L ^ { 2 }$ norm to prove stability. ",
        "bbox": [
